        "content": [
          "Nebensätze, or 'aside clauses'*, are",
          "triggered by SUBORDINATING CONJUNCTIONS.",
          "The verb in a Nebensatz goes to the END.",
          "",
          "COMMON SUBORDINATING CONJUNCTIONS:",
          "dass (that)  weil (because)  obwohl (although)",
          "wenn (when/if)  als (when-past)  ob (whether)",
          "",
          "NEBENSATZ IN SECOND HALF:",
          "Ich erkläre, dass ich Deutsch lerne.",
          "(I explain that I'm learning German)",
          "",
          "NEBENSATZ IN FIRST HALF:",
          "Wenn ich Zeit habe, lerne ich Deutsch.",
          "(When I have time, I learn German)",
          "",
          "*neben usually means 'besides', but 'aside'",
          "captures the role of this clause better."
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Lektion 28"
      },
      {
        "page": 2,
        "total_pages": 2,
        "content": [
          "TROTZDEM vs OBWOHL",
          "",
          "Both translate to 'although / nevertheless',",
          "but only OBWOHL triggers a Nebensatz.",
          "",
          "OBWOHL = subordinating conjunction",
          "→ verb goes to the END.",
          "Ich lerne, obwohl ich müde BIN.",
          "(I study, although I am tired)",
          "",
          "TROTZDEM = adverb (means 'nevertheless')",
          "→ verb stays in POSITION 2.",
          "Ich bin müde. Trotzdem LERNE ich.",
          "(I am tired. Nevertheless, I study.)",
          "",
          "Same meaning, different grammar:",
          "obwohl pushes the verb to the end,",
          "trotzdem keeps the verb in position 2."
        ]
      }
